approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

calcLatestRedemptionWindow().details: Prior to first redemption window, returns no window (i.e., start and end are 0). After that, returns the last (or current) window, until a new window is reached.

returns.windowEnd_: The end of the latest window
returns.windowStart_: The start of the latest window

cancelRequestDeposit(address).details: Can specify _depositAsset == NATIVE_ASSET to unwrap and receive native asset

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

deposit(address,uint256,uint256).details: Does not support deposits in fee-on-transfer tokens. Can specify _depositAsset == NATIVE_ASSET to wrap and deposit native asset.

params._depositAssetAmount: The amount of the asset to deposit

returns.sharesReceived_: The amount of wrapped shares received

params._depositAsset: The deposit asset of the requests

depositFromQueue(address,address[]).details: Unlike the redemption queue, there is no deposit window during which deposit requests are frozen. Since these requests are fluid, the manager can't rely on the queue's `users` array ordering, so user addresses are used as an input instead of request indexes.

params._depositAsset: The deposit asset of the requests

forceTransfer(address,address).details: Fully removes _sender from the redemption queue prior to transfer

getRedemptionQueue().details: Can't return a struct with a mapping in solc 0.6.12

returns.relativeSharesAllowed_: The relative shares allowed per-user during the window, as of the last checkpoint
returns.totalSharesPending_: The total shares pending in the queue

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

init(address,address[],address,bool,bool.details: The following vars initialize to their default value as they were added after the 1st version: - `depositMode`

params._depositMode: The mode to follow for deposits
params._managers: Users to give the role of manager for the wrapper
params._redemptionAsset: The asset to receive during shares redemptions
params._useDepositApprovals: True if deposit pre-approvals are required
params._useRedemptionApprovals: True if the redemption request pre-approvals are required
params._useTransferApprovals: True if shares transfer pre-approvals are required
params._vaultProxy: The VaultProxy that will have its shares wrapped

returns.isManager_: True if _user is a wrapper manager

kick(address).details: Must cleanup any approvals separately. If `redemptionAsset` is the native asset, the kicked user will receive the wrapped native asset instead (prevents reverting).

redeemFromQueue(uint256,uint256).details: If redemptions are not throttled by relativeSharesAllowed, always slice from the end of the queue (more efficient to remove all users from the queue)

params._endIndex: The final index of the slice
params._startIndex: The first index of the slice

returns.sharesRedeemed_: The amount of shares redeemed for each user

requestDeposit(address,uint256).details: Can specify _depositAsset == NATIVE_ASSET to wrap and deposit native asset

params._depositAssetAmount: The amount of the asset to deposit

params._sharesAmount: The amount of shares to add to the queue

params._assets: The deposit token for each approval
